__NOTOC__ A '''putative father''', with some variations in specific language, generally means a man whose legal relationship to a child has not been established but who is alleged to be or claims that he may be the [[biological father]] of a child who is born to a woman to whom he is not married at the time of the child's birth.<ref name=CWIG>{{cite news | author=Child Welfare Information Gateway | title=The Rights of Unmarried Fathers | url=http://www.childwelfare.gov/systemwide/laws_policies/statutes/putative.cfm | work=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services | date=30 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= http://legal-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/Putative+father | location=The Free Dictionary | title=Constitution and Laws of the United States | date=1856 |last=Bouvier | first=John | work=Law Dictionary}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= http://definitions.uslegal.com/p/putative-father/ | work= U.S. Legal .com | location= | title= Putative Father Law & Legal Definition | date= | first= | last= }}</ref><ref>{{ cite news | url= http://www.duhaime.org/LegalDictionary/P/Putativefather.aspx | work= | location= | title= Putative Father Definition | date= | first= Durhaime | last= Legal Dictionary}}</ref>
==United States== There is no standard definition for the word "father" in statutes across the United States. Five States (as of 2010, Arizona, Nebraska, New York, North Carolina, and Virginia{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}) as well as the [[District of Columbia]], [[American Samoa]], and the [[U.S. Virgin Islands]], provide no legal definition for the term at all.<ref name=CWIG/> Many states, however, have definitions for various categories of unwed fathers, with the term "putative father" being defined by statute in 13 States (as of 2017, these being Alabama<ref>http://alisondb.legislature.state.al.us/alison/codeofalabama/1975/26-10A-2.htm, </ref>Arkansas, Florida, Indiana, Iowa, Maine, Montana, Nevada, Ohio, Oklahoma, South Dakota, West Virginia, and Wyoming{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}).
